Rep. Jack Kemp, a New YorkRepublican, urged President Reagan to oppose any legislation toimpose a tax on stock transactions.    In a statement Kemp called the tax "a money grab to permitDemocrats to begin another government spending spree."    "I call upon President Reagan to signal immediately that hewill veto any tax increase on stock transfers," Kemp said. Headded that the tax would punish the 50 million stockholders.    House Speaker James Wright, a Texas Democrat, has askedcongressional tax analysts to look at a 0.25 to 0.5 pct tax onstock trades along with other tax proposals to help reduce thefederal budget deficit.                 Reuter&#3;